harges. Themotion was filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court in Manhattan.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush, prodded by congressionalleaders to do more for the new Polish government, has announced hewill double _ to $100 million _ next year's U.S. food aid to thatnation.   Foods to be sent to Poland, all coming from existing surpluses,include beef, pork, corn, butter, sunflower oil, cotton and rice.The new program was announced Thursday. The aid, for the fiscal yearthat begins Oct. 1, will follow $8.4 million in emergency food aidsent to Poland this year.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Orin Atkins, the former chairman and chiefexecutive officer of Ashland Oil Inc., has pleaded guilty to chargeshe tried to sell confidential company documents to an Iranian oilcompany involved in a dispute with Ashland.   Atkins, 65, of North Palm Beach, Fla., pleaded guilty Thursday inU.S. District Court to conspiracy and wire fraud. He faces a maximumof 10 years in prison and a $500,000 fine when sentenced Nov. 16.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government would come out ahead if itrepealed or relaxed a law that reduces the Social Security benefitsof senior citizens who earn more than a limited amount of outsideincome, a group of House Republicans says.   GOP critics of Social Security's earnings test released a privatestudy Thursday concluding that at least 700,000 retirees wouldrejoin the labor market if the law were scrapped. The new workerswould generate more in income and payroll taxes than the governmentwould pay out in increased Social Security benefits.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Junk bond trading slowed as the cash crunch atCampeau Corp. weighed heavily on the market, with tradersconsidering whether the company's problems were a forerunner oftrouble in a wide variety of the high-risk securities.   Trading slowed Thursday one day after admissions that Campeau'sAllied Stores Corp. and Federated Department Stores Inc. units coulddefault on their debt payments triggered a broad junk bond selloff.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Richard C. Breeden, President Bush's nominee tohead the Securities and Exchange Commission, told a Senate committeehe believed one can be a free marketeer and still be a tough cop onWall Street.   Illegal activities such as price fixing or insider trading are``an attack on the market itself,'' Breeden told the Senate Banking,Housing and Urban Affairs Committee at his confirmation hearingThursday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The House Ways and Means Committee has approveda cut in the capital gains tax, helping fulfill one of PresidentBush's campaign promises over the vehement objections of Democraticleaders.   The committee in a closed-door session Thursday approved the cut19-17 as six conservative Democrats sided with the 13 Republicans onthe panel.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market extended its September slump Thursday in sellingblamed on takeover-debt worries. The Dow Jones industrials average,down 27.74 points Wednesday, dropped another 14.63 to 2,664.89.   The dollar rebounded to finish higher in choppy U.S. dealings.   Treasury bonds and most corporate bonds rose but the junk bondmarket continued to weaken.   Copper for spot delivery surged to a 4{-month high; pork belliesrose the limit and grain futures rallied on news of a food-aidpackage to Poland; energy futures fell and precious metals weremixed.</TEXT></DOC>